1.1.2 Normalization and filtering

Start here for the workshop

Read in the BRCA RNA-seq data set and log-transform.

# Read mRNA expression data
all_brca_RNA <- readRDS(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/brca_RNA_TPM.rds"))
all_brca_RNA[1:5,1:5]
# use the gene symbol as the rownames, remove the other feature metadata
rownames(all_brca_RNA) <- all_brca_RNA$hugoGeneSymbol
all_brca_RNA <- all_brca_RNA[,-1:-3]
all_brca_RNA[1:5,1:5]

Log-scale, adding a pseudo-count.

all_brca_RNA.log2 <- log2(all_brca_RNA + 1)

Minimum expression filter: keep only those genes expressed in at least 30% of samples with log2(TPM)>0.

# Notes on this command:
#               1. Create boolean matrix based on values bigger than 0
#       2. Sum the rows: gets total number of samples with >0 expression
#                                       3. Compare to 30% of the number
#                                          of samples (total columns)
keep <- rowSums(all_brca_RNA.log2>0) >= 0.3 * ncol(all_brca_RNA.log2)
table(keep)
## keep
## FALSE  TRUE 
##  2197 18146
all_brca_RNA.log2.filtered <- all_brca_RNA.log2[keep,]

1.1.3 Make a balanced dataset

Ensure that the number of classes is balanced to avoid biasing the model.

library(tidyverse)
# Read clinical data
brca_cli <- readRDS(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/brca_clinical.rds"))
# Remove samples that are missing CANCER_TYPE_DETAILED metadata
brca_cli <- subset(brca_cli, !is.na(CANCER_TYPE_DETAILED))

Get samples of ductal and lobular types of breast cancer.

brca_cli.ductal <- brca_cli[
  brca_cli$CANCER_TYPE_DETAILED=="Breast Invasive Ductal Carcinoma",]
brca_cli.lobular <- brca_cli[
  brca_cli$CANCER_TYPE_DETAILED=="Breast Invasive Lobular Carcinoma",]
num_ductal <- nrow(brca_cli.ductal)
num_ductal
## [1] 812
num_lobular <- nrow(brca_cli.lobular)
num_lobular
## [1] 206

Since number of lobular samples is less than than ductal, select a subset of ductal samples so the data set is balanced.

set.seed(123)
ductal.samples <- sample(brca_cli.ductal$sampleId, num_lobular)
ductal.exp <- all_brca_RNA.log2.filtered[,ductal.samples]
lobular.samples <- brca_cli.lobular$sampleId
lobular.exp <- all_brca_RNA.log2.filtered[,lobular.samples]

# Combine ductal and lobular expression datasets
expr_combined <- cbind(ductal.exp, lobular.exp)
num_ductal <- num_lobular
labels <- c(rep("Ductal", num_ductal), rep("Lobular", num_lobular))
table(labels)
## labels
##  Ductal Lobular 
##     206     206
# Build data.frame for modeling: samples x genes
df <- as.data.frame(t(expr_combined))  # rows = samples, cols = genes
df <- tibble::rownames_to_column(df, var = "sample_id")
df$class <- factor(labels, levels = c("Ductal","Lobular"))

# Fix gene names to a format acceptable by R
colnames(df) <- make.names(colnames(df))

1.1.4 Split into training and testing cohorts

NOTE: if you need to catch up you can read in the df variable at this point.

df <- readRDS(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/ML_df.rds"))

Randomly split into training data (70%) and test data (30%). Note that setting the seed here is not necessaryin general but it ensures that these exercises are reproducible for the workshop.

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
set.seed(123)
train_idx <- createDataPartition(df$class, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)
train_df  <- df[train_idx, ]
test_df   <- df[-train_idx, ]

# For convenience, create x (data) and y (class labels)
x_train <- train_df %>% select(-sample_id, -class)
y_train <- train_df$class
x_test  <- test_df  %>% select(-sample_id, -class)
y_test  <- test_df$class

1.2 Feature selection

NOTE: if you need to catch up, load the required objects from our RData file. This will populate the following variables: x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, Xtr, Xte.

load(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/MLobjects.RData"))

Try two simple examples of feature selection: taking the top genes by variance and/or t-statistic.

1.2.1 Variance filtering of features

Compute variance per gene, and obtain the top 500 variable genes.

# Compute variance per gene
gene_vars <- sort(apply(x_train, 2, var), decreasing=TRUE)
head(gene_vars)
##   CLEC3A  SCGB2A2     CPB1  SCGB1D2    GSTM1    MUCL1 
## 26.53123 22.65776 21.95347 19.49457 19.36375 16.80111
# Keep top 500 variable genes (adjust as needed)
top_var_genes <- names(gene_vars)[1:500]
df_var_filtered <- x_train[, top_var_genes]
df_var_filtered[1:5,1:5]

1.2.2 T-test filtering of features

Run a t-test between Ductal and Lobular for each gene.

# T-test to rank remaining features
ttest_ranks <- apply(x_train, 2, function(g) {
  t.test(g ~ y_train)$statistic
})
ttest_ranks <- sort(abs(ttest_ranks), decreasing=TRUE)
head(ttest_ranks)
##     CDH1   SOWAHA  SHROOM1   PSMD14  RAPGEF3    FXYD1 
## 14.18417 10.54356 10.37435 10.14770 10.11638 10.02037

Pick the top 100 genes by their t-statistic.

# Pick the top 100 genes
top_ttest_genes <- names(ttest_ranks)[1:100]
df_ttest_filtered <- x_train[, top_ttest_genes]
df_ttest_filtered[1:5,1:5]

1.3 Logistic regression model with RFE

Use recursive feature elimination (RFE) to select the most informative features for a logistic regression model. For this we will start with the top 100 genes from the t-test filtering, and then filter down further with RFE.

library(caret)
library(ggplot2)

# RFE setup
rfe_ctrl <- rfeControl(functions = lrFuncs, 
                   method = "cv", # cross validation
                   number = 10) # number of folds

# Number of features to be retained in the updated model
sizes <- c(5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50)

# Run RFE
set.seed(123)
rfe_results <- rfe(
  x = df_ttest_filtered,
  y = y_train,
  sizes = sizes,
  rfeControl = rfe_ctrl
)

rfe_results

Xte <- x_test[, best_rfe_feats]

1.4 Test cohort and cross-validation with LR, cofusion matrix, ROC/AUC

NOTE: if you need to catch up, load the required objects from our RData file. This will populate the following variables: x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, Xtr, Xte.

load(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/MLobjects.RData"))

Run cross-validation and train the logistic regression model.

library(caret)
library(ggplot2)
library(pROC)

# Define cross-validation
lr_ctrl <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,              # 10-fold CV
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary, # Report ROC, Sensitivity, and Specificity
  savePredictions = "final"  # keep CV predictions
)

set.seed(123)
# Train logistic regression
lr_model <- train(
  x = Xtr,
  y = y_train,
  method = "glm",
  family = "binomial",
  trControl = lr_ctrl,
  metric = "ROC"
)
lr_model # CV results summary

## Resampling results:
## 
##   ROC        Sens       Spec     
##   0.9428277  0.8747619  0.8847619

Inspect the predictions from the model and evaluate.

2.1 Train an SVM model using the same predictors

NOTE: if you need to catch up, load the required objects from our RData file. This will populate the following variables: x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, Xtr, Xte. Also load the libraries.

library(caret)
library(ggplot2)
library(pROC)
load(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/MLobjects.RData"))

Train the SVM model.

  • Note that in practice you may want to choose a larger grid for tuning C.
  • If using a radial or polynomial kernel, you would also want to tune gamma.
library(kernlab)
svm_ctrl <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",   # cross-validation
  number = 10,     # 10-fold CV
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary, # Report ROC, Sensitivity, and Specificity
  savePredictions = "final"  # keep CV predictions
)

set.seed(123)
svm_model <- train(
  y_train ~ .,
  data = data.frame(y_train, Xtr),
  method = "svmLinear",
  trControl = svm_ctrl,
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(C = c(0.1, 1, 10)),
  metric = "ROC"
)
svm_model

2.1.1 Comparison of two models

Compare the logistic regression and SVM models, using the class prediction probabilities for Lobular.

We can formally test if one model is significantly better than the other with a Wilcoxon signed-rank test.

# recall the performance of each model from cross validation
lr_model$results$ROC
## [1] 0.9428277
max(svm_model$results$ROC)
## [1] 0.9417438
# use the probabilities for each model
logistic_lob <- prob_pred
svm_lob <- svm_probs[,"Lobular"]
head(logistic_lob)
## [1] 0.179989442 0.271200004 0.123590336 0.020214130 0.002743686 0.579122973
head(svm_lob)
## [1] 0.33800334 0.29609280 0.20957486 0.04474598 0.01662270 0.60078203
# set paired=T for the signed rank test
wilcox.test(logistic_lob, svm_lob, paired=T)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  logistic_lob and svm_lob
## V = 2945, p-value = 0.03946
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
# compare in a scatterplot
plot_df <- data.frame(Logistic=logistic_lob, SVM=svm_lob)
# basic R scatterplot
plot(plot_df)

2.2 Train a neural net model with regularization

NOTE: if you need to catch up, load the required objects from our RData file. This will populate the following variables: x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, Xtr, Xte. Also load the libraries.

library(caret)
library(ggplot2)
library(pROC)
load(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/MLobjects.RData"))

Train neural net with caret.

  • Running a hyperparameter grid search over size and decay parameters.
  • With 3 values for each of two parameters, so this will test 9 total parameter combinations.
nn_ctrl <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  savePredictions = "final"
)

set.seed(123)
nn_model <- train(
  y_train ~ .,
  data = data.frame(y_train, Xtr),
  method = "nnet",
  trControl = nn_ctrl,
  metric = "ROC",
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(
    size = c(3, 5, 7),   # hidden layer sizes to try
    decay = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1)  # regularization values
  ),
  trace = FALSE,
  maxit = 500
)

2.3.2 XGBoost model

Train XGB model.

library(caret)
library(pROC)
xgb_ctrl <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 10,
  classProbs = TRUE,
  summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
  savePredictions = "final",
  verboseIter = FALSE
)

set.seed(123)
xgb_model <- train(
  y_train ~ ., 
  data = data.frame(y_train, Xtr),
  method = "xgbTree",
  trControl = xgb_ctrl,
  metric = "ROC",
  tuneGrid = expand.grid(
    nrounds = c(50, 100),    # The total number of trees built sequentially
    max_depth = c(2, 3, 4), # maximum depth of a tree
    eta = c(0.05, 0.1, 0.3), # learning rate, shrinkage
    gamma = 0, # pruning parameter: 0 -> tree keeps splitting as long as it reduces error
    colsample_bytree = 1, # Fraction of features randomly chosen to build each tree
    min_child_weight = 1, # Controls the minimum amount of data needed in a leaf node
    subsample = 1 # Fraction of training data sampled for growing each tree
  ),
  verbosity = 0     # hides xgboost internal warnings
)

2.5 Predict survival probability

We are again using the breast cancer data set.

Load the clinical data and the variance-filtered genes if needed.

brca_cli <- readRDS(url("https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/brca_clinical.rds"))

  "https://wd.cri.uic.edu/machine_learning/brca.df.var_filt.rds"))

Data set up steps.

  • DFS_STATUS is the status of the tumor.
  • DFS_MONTHS is the follow-up time.
library(glmnet)
library(survival)
library(survcomp)
library(survminer)
# Get samples with complete cases of DFS_MONTHS and DFS_STATUS from the clinical data
keep <- complete.cases(brca_cli$DFS_MONTHS, 
                       brca_cli$DFS_STATUS) & brca_cli$DFS_MONTHS >= 0
DFS_MONTHS_clean <- brca_cli$DFS_MONTHS[keep]
summary(DFS_MONTHS_clean)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00   14.16   24.57   37.07   50.27  281.08
DFS_STATUS_clean <- brca_cli$DFS_STATUS[keep]
table(DFS_STATUS_clean)
## DFS_STATUS_clean
##         0:DiseaseFree 1:Recurred/Progressed 
##                   890                   113
brca.clean.df <- brca.df.var_filt[keep, ]

# Adjust 0 times
DFS_MONTHS_clean[DFS_MONTHS_clean == 0 & 
                   DFS_STATUS_clean == "1:Recurred/Progressed"] <- 0.001

# Drop 0-month censored patients
keep2 <- !(DFS_MONTHS_clean == 0 & DFS_STATUS_clean == "0:DiseaseFree")

DFS_MONTHS_clean <- DFS_MONTHS_clean[keep2]
DFS_STATUS_clean <- DFS_STATUS_clean[keep2]
brca.clean.df <- brca.clean.df[keep2, ]

# Build survival object
status <- ifelse(DFS_STATUS_clean == "1:Recurred/Progressed", 1, 0)
head(status)
## [1] 1 0 0 0 0 0
y <- Surv(time = DFS_MONTHS_clean, event = status)
head(y)
## [1] 12.71  10.91+ 11.33+ 11.27+ 10.41+ 12.32+
x <- as.matrix(brca.clean.df)

Fit the Cox regression model.

  • Note that this step is computationally intensive. In the interest of time we will make a smaller subset of the data so this runs faster.
  • You can try this exercise without the subsampling on your own.
set.seed(123)
# subset data for a faster processing time
subsample <- sample(1:length(y),400)
x <- x[subsample, ]
y <- y[subsample]
DFS_MONTHS_clean <- DFS_MONTHS_clean[subsample]
status <- status[subsample]
# fit the model
coxfit <- cv.glmnet(
  x, 
  y, 
  family = "cox",
  alpha = 1,              # LASSO
  nfolds = 5              # 5-fold CV
)
coxfit
## 
## Call:  cv.glmnet(x = x, y = y, nfolds = 5, family = "cox", alpha = 1) 
## 
## Measure: Partial Likelihood Deviance 
## 
##      Lambda Index Measure     SE Nonzero
## min 0.05209     6   11.74 0.4584       1
## 1se 0.06573     1   11.79 0.4455       0
# Best lambda
best_lambda <- coxfit$lambda.min

# Refit model at best lambda
coxfinal <- glmnet(x, 
                   y, 
                   family = "cox", 
                   alpha = 1, 
                   lambda = best_lambda)

# Get nonzero coefficients
cox_selected_genes <- rownames(coef(coxfinal))[coef(coxfinal)[,1] != 0]
length(cox_selected_genes)
## [1] 1
cox_selected_genes
## [1] "PPP4R4"
# Predicted risk score
risk_scores <- predict(coxfinal, newx = x, type = "link")

cindex <- concordance.index(
  x = risk_scores, 
  surv.time = DFS_MONTHS_clean,
  surv.event = status
)

cindex$c.index
## [1] 0.6952654
# Visualize Kaplan-Meier curves
risk_group <- ifelse(risk_scores > median(risk_scores), "High", "Low")
df.km <- data.frame(
  DFS_MONTHS = DFS_MONTHS_clean,
  status = status,
  risk_group = risk_group
)
fit_km <- survfit(Surv(DFS_MONTHS, status) ~ risk_group, data = df.km)
ggsurvplot(fit_km, data = df.km, pval = TRUE, risk.table = TRUE, risk.table.height = 0.25)

3.1.3 Feature elimination and RFE with logistic regression

# T-test to rank remaining features
ttest_ranks <- apply(x_train, 2, function(g) {
  t.test(g ~ y_train)$statistic
})
ttest_ranks <- sort(abs(ttest_ranks), decreasing = TRUE)

# Pick the top 100 genes
top_ttest_genes <- names(ttest_ranks)[1:100]
df_ttest_filtered <- x_train[, top_ttest_genes]

# Number of features to be retained in the updated model
sizes <- c(5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45, 50)

# Perform RFE
set.seed(123)
rfe_ctrl <- rfeControl(functions = lrFuncs, 
                   method = "cv", # cross validation
                   number = 10) # number of folds
rfe_results_all <- rfe(
  x = df_ttest_filtered,
  y = y_train,
  sizes = sizes,   # candidate numbers of features
  rfeControl = rfe_ctrl
)

metrics_text <- paste0("R2 = ", round(r2_rf, 3),
                       " RMSE = ", round(rmse_rf, 2))
ggplot(df_pred, aes(x = Observed, y = Predicted)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=1, linetype="dashed") +
  labs(title = "Random Forest Regression: Predicted vs Observed Age",
    subtitle = metrics_text,
    x = "Observed Age",
    y = "Predicted Age")
